    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-09-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-09-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="254"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d254">
                <head>254. Memorandum for the Record<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d254fn1"
                        >Source: National Security Council, Intelligence Files, 303 Committee,
                        Minutes – 1964. Secret; Eyes Only. Prepared on September 11.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-09-10">September 10, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Minutes of the Meeting of the 303 Committee, 10 September 1964</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PRESENT</head>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BMG_1">Bundy</persName>, Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_THB_1">Thompson</persName>, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                            >Vance</persName>, and Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MJA_1"
                            >McCone</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Colonel Ralph D. Steakley was present for Item 1</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of other subjects.]</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">
                    <hi rend="roman">7.</hi> Congo</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MJA_1">McCone</persName> brought up the subject of
                    covert support [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line not declassified</hi>] and
                    said he hoped the time was near when the C–130’s could be withdrawn and with
                    them, most of the U.S. military support force. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                        >Vance</persName> estimated that withdrawal of the C–130’s would result in a
                    reduction of no more than 125 personnel, leaving approximately <pb facs="0402"
                        n="369" xml:id="pg_369"/> the same number for other required tasks,
                    including T–28 maintenance. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MJA_1">McCone</persName>
                    indicated that two C–54’s and several C–46’s were earmarked to satisfy the
                    Congolese government lift requirements and handling and maintenance would be
                    supervised by a Panamanian company which was recruiting in Europe; this would
                    reduce the American presence. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MJA_1">McCone</persName>
                    added that it was his impression that considering the prejudices against
                        <persName corresp="#p_TMK_1">Tshombe</persName> in Addis Ababa, both self
                    imposed and otherwise, he had emerged relatively unscathed and with some degree
                    of stature.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of another subject.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JPE_1">Peter Jessup</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
